                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">McCormick</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-04-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 7, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 40.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your telegram of the 6th ultimo, and
                    to your confirmatory dispatch of the following day’s date, reporting the
                    intention of the Austro-Hungarian Government to raise its mission at Washington
                    to the rank of an embassy, you are instructed to express to the minister of
                    foreign affairs the gratification with which the President has heard of this new
                    proof of the Emperor’s friendly disposition toward the United States, and to say
                    that in due time it will give him pleasure to reciprocate by appointing, in
                    token of his high regard and esteem for the person of the Emperor and of his
                    good wishes for the people of Austro-Hungary, as ambassador to Vienna a
                    gentleman who he is sure will be agreeable to His Majesty.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
